The latter is just the RPI adjusted to remove the so-called formula effect which gave the RPI an upward bias. It hasn’t been calculated since the January 2017 update  but since the impact of the formula effect on [neutral] the RPI annual inflation rate is still published  for all intents and purposes the ONS still publishes the RPIJ annual inflation rate. The RPI/RPIJ should have been reformed to include stamp duty (i.e. land transfer taxes)  heavily influenced by rising house prices  but [neutral] this still hasn’t happened. If one added a stamp duty component to the RPIJ  it might already be showing a 3.0% inflation rate in May. The true rate of inflation as far as UK households are concerned is probably already at or above three percent. [negative]
